Day 4-A Activity
(Support Vector Machines)

Let’s try to predict whether it is safe or unsafe for humans to drink from a water source based on its chemical properties (e.g., pH, hardness, sulfate content).

Load packages

Note that {caret} may ask you to install the {kernlab} package

library(tidyverse)
library(caret)
library(skimr)
library(recipes)
library(yardstick)

Read in the data

water <- read_csv("https://bit.ly/amlr-water")
water

Explore the data

Create recipe (including imputation of missing predictor values!)

water_recipe <- 
  water %>% 
  recipe(Potability ~ .) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_impute_knn(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors())

Set up a shared configuration for resampling

water_tc <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

Let {kernlab} estimate sigma automatically

set.seed(2021)
water_autosig <- train(
  water_recipe,
  data = water,
  method = "svmRadial",
  tuneLength = 5, # try 5 values of C only (estimate just one sigma)
  trControl = water_tc
)
water_autosig

Use gridsearch to tune sigma

Note that this may take a few minutes…

set.seed(2021)
water_tunesig <- train(
  water_recipe,
  data = water,
  method = "svmRadialSigma", # try 5 values of C and 5 values of sigma
  tuneLength = 5,
  trControl = water_tc
)
water_tunesig

Hands-on Activity

Let’s try to predict whether an employee with quit their job based on various measures.

  1. Load the attrition dataset from the {modeldata} package (Hint: use data(...))
  2. Explore the data and create a recipe that includes at least normalization and dummy coding
  3. Configure your resampling to be a single 10-fold cross-validation (or 5-fold if your computer is slow)
  4. Train models using the following algorithms to classify the Potability variable
    • GLMNET with a tuneLength of 5 for \(\alpha\) and \(\lambda\)
    • SVM with RBF kernel with a tuneLength of 5 for \(C\) (let {kernlab} estimate \(\sigma\))
  5. Collect the two sets of resampling results using resamples() and plot them using bwplot()

Answer Key

Click here to see the answer key for the hands-on activity

Load and examine data

data("attrition", package = "modeldata")
attrition

Configure recipe

attr_recipe <- 
  attrition %>% 
  recipe(Attrition ~ .) %>% 
  step_nzv(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_corr(all_predictors()) %>% 
  step_lincomb(all_predictors())

Configure resampling

attr_tc <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

Train GLMNET

set.seed(2021)
attr_glmnet <- train(
  attr_recipe,
  data = attrition,
  method = "glmnet",
  tuneLength = 5,
  trControl = attr_tc
)

  trControl = attr_tc
